00:26:58.230 --> 00:27:00.060
called barbecue shrimp.

00:27:00.060 --> 00:27:01.560
It's not grilled.

00:27:01.560 --> 00:27:03.490
It doesn't have barbecue sauce.

00:27:03.490 --> 00:27:06.277
I don't understand this dish.

00:27:06.277 --> 00:27:07.360
Why is it called barbecue?

00:27:07.360 --> 00:27:08.050
It's delicious.

00:27:08.050 --> 00:27:09.490
It's very peppery,
Worcestershire.

00:27:09.490 --> 00:27:12.110
EMERIL LAGASSE: Well, I think
probably one of the originals.

00:27:12.110 --> 00:27:14.210
It really started
as a home dish.

00:27:14.210 --> 00:27:18.600
And we're very
fortunate in Louisiana

00:27:18.600 --> 00:27:21.440
and along the coast in
Florida and Mississippi

00:27:21.440 --> 00:27:24.540
to have really, truly an
abundance and easy way

00:27:24.540 --> 00:27:27.100
to access shrimp pretty easily.

00:27:27.100 --> 00:27:29.160
Shrimp boats are everywhere.

00:27:29.160 --> 00:27:32.410
You go in New Orleans,
you'll find these trucks

00:27:32.410 --> 00:27:35.150
that have ice chest
that are selling shrimp.

00:27:35.150 --> 00:27:36.680
It's amazing.

00:27:36.680 --> 00:27:40.610
So my research tells
me that basically it

00:27:40.610 --> 00:27:43.480
was a home dish that
moms and dads used

00:27:43.480 --> 00:27:47.220
to do with a lot of butter,
Worcestershire sauce, which

00:27:47.220 --> 00:27:55.350
is a big staple of the cooking,
garlic, and maybe some onion.

00:27:55.350 --> 00:27:59.270
And then when it
commercialized, it probably

00:27:59.270 --> 00:28:03.300
made its mark at Pascal
Manale's in uptown New Orleans,

00:28:03.300 --> 00:28:05.530
where you have to have a bib.

00:28:05.530 --> 00:28:10.500
Because it's almost like a
vinaigrette, if you will.

00:28:10.500 --> 00:28:12.050
It's like Worcestershire
and butter

00:28:12.050 --> 00:28:14.990
that's separated with a
lot of cracked pepper.

00:28:14.990 --> 00:28:19.200
And you dip it, and
you get crusty bread.

00:28:19.200 --> 00:28:21.210
And no, there's
nobody barbecue sauce,

00:28:21.210 --> 00:28:25.420
and they're not on the grill,
and they're not on the barbie.

00:28:25.420 --> 00:28:27.630
So that's where that started.

00:28:27.630 --> 00:28:34.690
Now, Emeril's this year,
this coming March, actually,

00:28:34.690 --> 00:28:38.770
will be 25 years that Emeril's
has been open, my flagship.

00:28:38.770 --> 00:28:43.840
And when I was
creating Emeril's there

00:28:43.840 --> 00:28:47.630
were few dishes that I
wanted to do and create

00:28:47.630 --> 00:28:49.750
for a white
tablecloth restaurant.

00:28:49.750 --> 00:28:50.850
I didn't say fine dining.

00:28:50.850 --> 00:28:53.710
I said white tablecloth.

00:28:53.710 --> 00:28:56.850
And one of them was I wanted
to do barbecue shrimp.

00:28:56.850 --> 00:29:01.530
So what we did is we took the
shrimp, and we took the heads

00:29:01.530 --> 00:29:06.440
and took the shells, and we
made an extraction or a barbecue

00:29:06.440 --> 00:29:08.720
base, even though it's
not a barbecue sauce.

00:29:08.720 --> 00:29:13.330
Heavy Worcestershire,
lots of herbs and spices,

00:29:13.330 --> 00:29:15.970
pepper, of course,
Worcestershire, lemons.

00:29:15.970 --> 00:29:18.590
And this is reduced down.

00:29:18.590 --> 00:29:20.880
It's a slow process,
a reduction.

00:29:20.880 --> 00:29:25.570
It makes not quite a
paste, but more of a syrup.

00:29:25.570 --> 00:29:29.520
And that's what we use, of
course with a little cream

00:29:29.520 --> 00:29:31.690
and butter, the things
are the good for you.

00:29:31.690 --> 00:29:33.480
And that's our barbecue shrimp.

00:29:33.480 --> 00:29:36.010
And I created that, and it was
one of the very first dishes

00:29:36.010 --> 00:29:37.630
that we put on the menu.

00:29:37.630 --> 00:29:39.290
And the flavor of
it is just what

00:29:39.290 --> 00:29:41.980
you've experienced,
except there's no mess.

00:29:41.980 --> 00:29:44.060
It's a knife and fork
deal, and we serve it

00:29:44.060 --> 00:29:47.100
with a petite rosemary biscuit.

00:29:47.100 --> 00:29:49.450
So now everybody has
their variation on that.

00:29:49.450 --> 00:29:53.720
But it's also fun to do
at the beach, because it's

00:29:53.720 --> 00:29:56.310
an easy dish that
you can get shrimp,

00:29:56.310 --> 00:30:00.550
and you can either make a
stock or not with the shells,

00:30:00.550 --> 00:30:03.390
or you basically just
put them in a cast iron

00:30:03.390 --> 00:30:06.550
with a lot of butter and parsley
and garlic and Worcestershire

00:30:06.550 --> 00:30:10.290
sauce, and you simmer
them up until they cook,

00:30:10.290 --> 00:30:12.030
and you serve them
with crusty bread.

00:30:12.030 --> 00:30:13.510
TY PENNINGTON: But shrimp
