lot of television,

00:33:51.690 --> 00:33:54.030
but I did love his show.

00:33:54.030 --> 00:33:56.570
I loved his connection
with people.

00:33:56.570 --> 00:33:58.430
And then he and I did
a project together

00:33:58.430 --> 00:34:02.790
for Good Morning
America where Ty

00:34:02.790 --> 00:34:04.252
rebuilt a hospital for children.

00:34:04.252 --> 00:34:05.710
TY PENNINGTON: Give
kids the world.

00:34:05.710 --> 00:34:06.584
EMERIL LAGASSE: Yeah.

00:34:06.584 --> 00:34:10.050
And I was part of it and
did the food part of it

00:34:10.050 --> 00:34:11.679
for the hospital.

00:34:11.679 --> 00:34:14.090
And we met, and we
sort of connected.

00:34:14.090 --> 00:34:15.960
And what we really
didn't know is

00:34:15.960 --> 00:34:18.310
that his agent was
working on this show,

00:34:18.310 --> 00:34:20.139
and my agent was
working on this show.

00:34:20.139 --> 00:34:23.219
But he and I couldn't really
say anything to each other.

00:34:23.219 --> 00:34:28.639
And then shortly after, Mark
Burnett and his team, Mark

00:34:28.639 --> 00:34:32.730
Burnett Productions, said,
hey we got this great show.

00:34:32.730 --> 00:34:34.949
You guys should
think about this.

00:34:34.949 --> 00:34:36.690
You guys would be
great together.

00:34:36.690 --> 00:34:38.389
And it really has been a blast.

00:34:38.389 --> 00:34:40.659
We're really happy.

00:34:40.659 --> 00:34:41.870
I'm sticking to my story.

00:34:41.870 --> 00:34:43.400
TY PENNINGTON: Yeah.

00:34:43.400 --> 00:34:46.110
It's funny, I'm
really good friends

00:34:46.110 --> 00:34:48.929
with a lady who works
with Mark Burnett.

00:34:48.929 --> 00:34:51.446
She's a very lady in television.

00:34:51.446 --> 00:34:53.070
I've worked with her
on several things.

00:34:53.070 --> 00:34:54.750
And she called me
one day and was

00:34:54.750 --> 00:34:57.750
like, hey, I've got this show
idea that I'd like you hear.

00:34:57.750 --> 00:35:01.440
And I was like, you want
me to host a cooking show?

00:35:01.440 --> 00:35:03.610
She's like, well,
it's more than that.

00:35:03.610 --> 00:35:05.270
And I was like,
OK, let's hear it.

00:35:05.270 --> 00:35:07.610
And then she said, you'd
be working with Emeril.

00:35:07.610 --> 00:35:11.320
And I was like, I
like it already.

00:35:11.320 --> 00:35:16.150
But as she unlaid what
makes the show so different

00:35:16.150 --> 00:35:18.160
and the fact that we're
working with home cooks,

00:35:18.160 --> 00:35:20.460
that you really are
dreaming, and I realized,

00:35:20.460 --> 00:35:22.640
wow, this is a
chance to really see

00:35:22.640 --> 00:35:24.787
somebody who's got a
passion about something

00:35:24.787 --> 00:35:25.620
really live a dream.

00:35:25.620 --> 00:35:27.079
At the same time,
it's a challenge.

00:35:27.079 --> 00:35:28.661
You don't know what's
going to happen.

00:35:28.661 --> 00:35:29.745
It's got high energy.

00:35:29.745 --> 00:35:33.790
And clearly that's why I was
brought in-- for the energy.

00:35:33.790 --> 00:35:36.750
And what's fun
about Emeril is, we

00:35:36.750 --> 00:35:38.797
didn't really know
each other too well.

00:35:38.797 --> 00:35:41.380
We were both surprised by each
other's sort of sense of humor,

00:35:41.380 --> 00:35:42.850
but we have two
different styles.

00:35:42.850 --> 00:35:45.550
We're sort of like
Bert and Ernie.

00:35:45.550 --> 00:35:50.195
One is like, and is like--
barely says anything,

00:35:50.195 --> 00:35:53.020
but when he says it, it's good.

00:35:53.020 --> 00:35:55.580
So it's fun.

00:35:55.580 --> 00:36:00.720
I think it's a fun
show because he

00:36:00.720 --> 00:36:04.600
gets to lend his expertise
to people who really need it.

00:36:07.960 --> 00:36:11.030
Why is that funny?

00:36:11.030 --> 00:36:13.730
And I just get to
lend non-sequiturs,

00:36:13.730 --> 00:36:16.520
which is also my gift.

00:36:16.520 --> 00:36:17.825
So it's a lot of fun.

00:36:17.825 --> 00:36:21.136
MALE SPEAKER: I think there
was a question over here.

00:36:21.136 --> 00:36:23.020
AUDIENCE: Thank
you for being here.

00:36:23.020 --> 00:36:26.810
So I'm pregnant, and when I have
my midnight craving for gumbo

00:36:26.810 --> 00:36:29.640
but I don't have three
hours to make a roux,

00:36:29.640 --> 00:36:34.280
what can I whip up that's the
essence of New Orleans in five

00:36:34.280 --> 00:36:36.837
minutes that will give me that
spicy gumbo taste and then

00:36:36.837 --> 00:36:37.920
I can just go back to bed?

00:36:37.920 --> 00:36:39.816
TY PENNINGTON: That's
a good question.

00:36:39.816 --> 00:36:41.355
EMERIL LAGASSE:
Do you eat pasta?

00:36:41.355 --> 00:36:43.721
AUDIENCE: I eat everything.

00:36:43.721 --> 00:36:45.652
TY PENNINGTON: I'm pregnant.

00:36:45.652 --> 00:36:48.400
EMERIL LAGASSE:
If you have pasta

00:36:48.400 --> 00:36:51.005
and you have this stuff, this
essence stuff, this spice--

00:36:51.005 --> 00:36:52.391
AUDIENCE: Where do you get that?

00:36:52.391 --> 00:36:54.390
EMERIL LAGASSE: It's in
a lot of grocery stores.

00:36:54.390 --> 00:36:56.260
TY PENNINGTON: It's
in the essence aisle.

00:36:56.260 --> 00:36:57.780
Next to Emeril's--

00:36:57.780 --> 00:37:01.010
EMERIL LAGASSE: But any
kind of Creole seasoning.

00:37:01.010 --> 00:37:04.730
And if you even just used
olive oil, not even cream base,

00:37:04.730 --> 00:37:08.310
if you used olive oil
and sprinkled that on,

00:37:08.310 --> 00:37:12.210
and you had a protein,
maybe some smoked sausage,

00:37:12.210 --> 00:37:14.610
you'd be really close.

00:37:14.610 --> 00:37:17.423
And that would be less
than 20 minutes, probably.

00:37:17.423 --> 00:37:19.180
AUDIENCE: And Tums for dessert.

00:37:19.180 --> 00:37:20.263
EMERIL LAGASSE: I'm sorry?

00:37:20.263 --> 00:37:22.390
TY PENNINGTON: Tums, yeah,
to take the edge off.

00:37:22.390 --> 00:37:23.050
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:37:23.050 --> 00:37:23.780
EMERIL LAGASSE: Yeah.

00:37:23.780 --> 00:37:25.530
There's nothing wrong
with bananas foster.

00:37:28.407 --> 00:37:29.240
AUDIENCE: Hey, guys.

00:37:29.240 --> 00:37:30.990
Just wanted to say thanks for
taking the time to do this.

00:37:30.990 --> 00:37:31.550
EMERIL LAGASSE: Thank you.

00:37:31.550 --> 00:37:33.140
AUDIENCE: I was
surprised that you

00:37:33.140 --> 00:37:37.200
said you thought home cooks were
better today than in the past.

00:37:37.200 --> 00:37:39.530
With Seamless and everything
now, and going out

00:37:39.530 --> 00:37:41.120
to eat-- even when I was
young, it was a special thing.

00:37:41.120 --> 00:37:42.035
And now that I'm
getting older, it

00:37:42.035 --> 00:37:43.576
seems like everybody
can get take out

00:37:43.576 --> 00:37:46.360
so easily, that food has
because so much more accessible.

00:37:46.360 --> 00:37:48.180
I would be surprised
if more people were

00:37:48.180 --> 00:37:50.270
cooking at home now than before.

00:37:50.270 --> 00:37:53.010
So I was just wondering if you
had any reason why you thought

00:37:53.010 --> 00:37:54.468
people were better
now than before?

00:37:54.468 --> 00:37:56.792
Is just more
information, or what?

00:37:56.792 --> 00:37:59.000
TY PENNINGTON: You probably
got all the good answers.

00:37:59.000 --> 00:38:01.360
I would say in the
past, it was usually

00:38:01.360 --> 00:38:03.360
one person cooking
in the family.

00:38:03.360 --> 00:38:07.100
But I think, let's just say,
modern family has really

00:38:07.100 --> 00:38:08.820
evolved in all kinds
of different ways.

00:38:08.820 --> 00:38:11.010
So more people are cooking.

00:38:11.010 --> 00:38:13.930
But I think there's more ideas.

00:38:13.930 --> 00:38:16.180
There's more visuals.

00:38:16.180 --> 00:38:18.490
Because of cooking shows,
more people are trying it.

00:38:18.490 --> 00:38:20.640
Where some people say,
oh, I can't do it,

00:38:20.640 --> 00:38:21.940
or well, maybe I'll try it.

00:38:21.940 --> 00:38:23.040
So that's what I mean.

00:38:23.040 --> 00:38:26.840
I think there's more volume
of people trying it at home.

00:38:26.840 --> 00:38:29.400
There's certainly a lot better
restaurants these days, I

00:38:29.400 --> 00:38:34.860
think, just because they've
amped up the game a little bit.

00:38:34.860 --> 00:38:37.360
EMERIL LAGASSE: Yeah, the game
has definitely changed a lot,

00:38:37.360 --> 00:38:39.540
and at home as well.

00:38:39.540 --> 00:38:44.150
There are more people in
the household cooking now

00:38:44.150 --> 00:38:45.800
than ever.

00:38:45.800 --> 00:38:47.670
You guys are the
kings of that stuff,

00:38:47.670 --> 00:38:49.330
knowing that statistic stuff.

00:38:52.410 --> 00:38:55.220
Just about everybody
I meet these days

00:38:55.220 --> 00:38:59.710
are trying at some level about
cooking, or at least wanting

00:38:59.710 --> 00:39:03.590
to try at some level.

00:39:03.590 --> 00:39:08.530
And then there are a lot
of things that have passed.

00:39:08.530 --> 00:39:12.220
For a while, there
was a craze that folks

00:39:12.220 --> 00:39:15.640
were having these weekend
parties where they were trying

00:39:15.640 --> 00:39:18.990
to do Iron Chef things and
couples against couples

00:39:18.990 --> 00:39:21.489
against couples, and a lot of
fun things started happening.

00:39:21.489 --> 00:39:22.780
TY PENNINGTON: Like salmonella.

00:39:22.780 --> 00:39:25.270
[LAUGHTER]

00:39:25.770 --> 00:39:31.744
So I say all around, it's
got nothing but better.

00:39:31.744 --> 00:39:33.160
MALE SPEAKER: I
think we have time

00:39:33.160 --> 00:39:34.701
for just one more
question over here.

00:39:34.701 --> 00:39:35.452
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:39:35.452 --> 00:39:38.140
I'm curious about your process
for finding the restaurant

00:39:38.140 --> 00:39:39.640
partners for you show.

00:39:39.640 --> 00:39:42.550
Was there a level of variety
you were looking for?

00:39:42.550 --> 00:39:44.020
What was the thought
behind who you

00:39:44.020 --> 00:39:48.615
picked to be the restaurants
that choose the dishes?

00:39:48.615 --> 00:39:50.490
TY PENNINGTON: I love
that you pass it to me.

00:39:50.490 --> 00:39:52.240
Well, thank you so
much for your question.

00:39:58.330 --> 00:40:01.110
I honestly think it was
a simple thing where

00:40:01.110 --> 00:40:03.330
TNT put the word
out that look, we're

00:40:03.330 --> 00:40:06.380
going to show that is really
going to showcase home

00:40:06.380 --> 00:40:10.870
cooks in a challenge to put
it on everyday restaurants

00:40:10.870 --> 00:40:13.950
and chains.

00:40:13.950 --> 00:40:17.650
Hats off to some
of the restaurants

00:40:17.650 --> 00:40:18.990
who wanted to take a risk.

00:40:18.990 --> 00:40:21.219
Because it is a risk when
it's a television show.

00:40:21.219 --> 00:40:23.510
But more than that, these
guys, you've got to remember,

00:40:23.510 --> 00:40:26.310
they're not just being involved.

00:40:26.310 --> 00:40:28.650
On Friday night
when the show airs,

00:40:28.650 --> 00:40:33.907
Chili's kitchen staff with
restaurants over the country

00:40:33.907 --> 00:40:36.240
are finally understanding
what ingredients are going in.

00:40:36.240 --> 00:40:38.310
Because nobody even
there knows yet

00:40:38.310 --> 00:40:40.526
until the show airs
on Friday night, which

00:40:40.526 --> 00:40:41.900
means that entire
staff has to be

00:40:41.900 --> 00:40:44.990
ready to create that
dish for Saturday.

00:40:44.990 --> 00:40:46.510
So it's a big commitment.

00:40:46.510 --> 00:40:47.130
And I think--

00:40:47.130 --> 00:40:50.585
EMERIL LAGASSE: And the
execution is incredible.

00:40:50.585 --> 00:40:53.890
TY PENNINGTON: It's
pretty-- well, like I said,

00:40:53.890 --> 00:40:55.590
I think what's
astounding about it

00:40:55.590 --> 00:40:57.260
is it's never been done before.

00:40:57.260 --> 00:40:59.820
And it is a big step forward.

00:40:59.820 --> 00:41:01.320
But I think it's
one of those things

00:41:01.320 --> 00:41:05.670
that as far as integration
goes and as far synergy,

00:41:05.670 --> 00:41:07.330
you're still having
good entertainment.

00:41:07.330 --> 00:41:09.829
You're also learning a lot about
food, but at the same time,

00:41:09.829 --> 00:41:13.140
you're also giving--
advertising is changing, too.

00:41:13.140 --> 00:41:16.610
And so if you can deliver
that and it works,

00:41:16.610 --> 00:41:18.570
it could be groundbreaking.

00:41:18.570 --> 00:41:21.552
So it's going to be
interesting to see.

00:41:21.552 --> 00:41:23.260
Again, we haven't
answered your question,

00:41:23.260 --> 00:41:26.410
but we have talked for a while.

00:41:26.410 --> 00:41:29.520
EMERIL LAGASSE: I think
that TNT did really

00:41:29.520 --> 00:41:33.270
a super job of getting
the word out in America

00:41:33.270 --> 00:41:35.620
that this was going to happen.

00:41:35.620 --> 00:41:38.310
People then submitted
recipes to them.

00:41:38.310 --> 00:41:42.510
And it was actually a process
that had to go through that.

00:41:42.510 --> 00:41:46.440
And then these
people were selected.

00:41:46.440 --> 00:41:48.270
And it's their dishes.

00:41:48.270 --> 00:41:50.180
It could be their
grandmother's, it could

00:41:50.180 --> 00:41:52.280
be their aunt's, their
uncle's, whatever.

00:41:52.280 --> 00:41:55.690
But it's their interpretation
of that dish or their dish.

00:41:55.690 --> 00:41:57.880
And they're doing
everything they

00:41:57.880 --> 00:42:00.800
can to try to get
it on the menu.

00:42:00.800 --> 00:42:02.420
TY PENNINGTON: To
change it enough

00:42:02.420 --> 00:42:06.459
that it would work on the
menu of whatever restaurant

00:42:06.459 --> 00:42:07.250
we're working with.

00:42:07.250 --> 00:42:08.610
EMERIL LAGASSE: That's
an important thing, too,

00:42:08.610 --> 00:42:09.580
Ty, like you just said.

00:42:09.580 --> 00:42:14.440
Because not everything
submitted can possibly

00:42:14.440 --> 00:42:16.780
be either afforded or executed.

00:42:16.780 --> 00:42:19.030
TY PENNINGTON: And 120
ingredients isn't going to fly.

00:42:19.030 --> 00:42:20.090
EMERIL LAGASSE: Exactly.

00:42:20.090 --> 00:42:22.740
TY PENNINGTON: But I think
they did really one of variety.

00:42:22.740 --> 00:42:24.949
Because you can't
just have hamburgers.

00:42:24.949 --> 00:42:25.990
You can't just have this.

00:42:25.990 --> 00:42:28.180
You need a variety
of restaurants,

00:42:28.180 --> 00:42:31.650
because you need to hit the
gamut of breakfast, dinner,

00:42:31.650 --> 00:42:33.170
lunch, dessert.

00:42:33.170 --> 00:42:35.930
So you want it to be able
to be constantly changing

00:42:35.930 --> 00:42:40.320
so that there can be surprises
for the taste buds every week.

00:42:40.320 --> 00:42:42.390
EMERIL LAGASSE: And we
have an amazing kitchen

00:42:42.390 --> 00:42:44.697
staff on the show,
really amazing.

00:42:44.697 --> 00:42:46.280
TY PENNINGTON: Great
medic staff, too.

00:42:46.280 --> 00:42:47.570
Just ready at any moment.

00:42:47.570 --> 00:42:51.860
EMERIL LAGASSE: A lot
of Band Aids, flu shots.

00:42:51.860 --> 00:42:56.360
But the pantry has to
be completely stocked,

00:42:56.360 --> 00:42:58.790
because we don't know what
direction they're going to go.

00:42:58.790 --> 00:43:00.900
So it's a really big challenge.

00:43:00.900 --> 00:43:04.520
It's a big shot for them
every other day on the set.

00:43:04.520 --> 00:43:08.500
Because it's not only
proteins, but it's produce

00:43:08.500 --> 00:43:11.397
and the freshest, greatest
ingredients that we can get.

00:43:11.397 --> 00:43:12.480
TY PENNINGTON: It's funny.

00:43:12.480 --> 00:43:18.580
I try and put myself in the
place of one of the home cooks.

00:43:18.580 --> 00:43:20.220
I was thinking to
myself, OK, I think

00:43:20.220 --> 00:43:21.700
I'm good enough that
I can create something

00:43:21.700 --> 00:43:22.950
that maybe somebody would dig.

00:43:22.950 --> 00:43:25.310
But I'm dumb enough to
pitch these really bad ideas

00:43:25.310 --> 00:43:27.685
to the corporate executives
just because I'm sitting next

00:43:27.685 --> 00:43:29.620
to them, and they're
just like, what?

00:43:29.620 --> 00:43:31.640
But I'm like, it could work.

00:43:31.640 --> 00:43:38.350
So anyway, my point is that it's
not just creating this dish,

00:43:38.350 --> 00:43:41.240
but then realizing they
have to whip out 40 plates.

00:43:41.240 --> 00:43:43.794
So you mainly go
from this person

00:43:43.794 --> 00:43:45.960
has been cooking for your
family to, oh, by the way,

00:43:45.960 --> 00:43:47.769
you've got to go feed a room.

00:43:47.769 --> 00:43:49.810
And they all have to be
delivered, because each--

00:43:49.810 --> 00:43:52.059
EMERIL LAGASSE: And they're
customers of these places.

00:43:52.059 --> 00:43:54.170
So they know the menu
and their product.

00:43:54.170 --> 00:43:56.240
TY PENNINGTON: And
then it hits you--

00:43:56.240 --> 00:44:00.025
wait, maybe I couldn't do this.

00:44:00.025 --> 00:44:02.400
I can deliver one and be like,
you're going to love this.

00:44:02.400 --> 00:44:04.730
But 40-- what?

00:44:04.730 --> 00:44:07.200
So it's fun.

00:44:07.200 --> 00:44:09.469
And it's a great challenge.

00:44:09.469 --> 00:44:11.510
MALE SPEAKER: Well, I
think you guys have to run.

00:44:11.510 --> 00:44:12.360
They've got a busy schedule.

00:44:12.360 --> 00:44:13.500
I want to thank you
guys for coming.

00:44:13.500 --> 00:44:15.125
Please, everyone,
give them a big hand.

00:44:15.125 --> 00:44:18.350
[APPLAUSE]

